  "uuid": "6f4256c4-8e87-4dc9-a307-5dc7043d55f3",
  "name": "Finding the service used to train a LoRA",
  "summary": "**Conversation Overview**\n\nThe user needed to identify which service they had previously used to train a LoRA (Low-Rank Adaptation) model. Claude searched past conversations and determined the user had used Unsloth via Google Colab for their machine learning project. The training setup involved using a free T4 GPU on Google Colab with Unsloth for 2x faster fine-tuning and 4-bit quantization. The user worked with a Qwen2.5-3B base model and trained on the \"Ah4b/Luna-director-dataset-001\" dataset from HuggingFace containing 147 examples. The training produced approximately 120MB of adapter weights saved to \"/src/training/luna_director_3b_lora/\" with a configuration using rank 16, alpha 16, targeting specific projection layers. The user requested the link to access their training notebook, which was stored locally at \"/Users/zayneamason/_HeyLuna_BETA/_Eclessi_BetaProject_Root/src/training/Luna_Director_Unsloth_Training.ipynb\". Claude explained that since the notebook was designed for Google Colab, the user would need to upload it manually to colab.research.google.com or check their recent Colab files for a previously saved version named \"Luna Director.\"\n\n**Tool Knowledge**\n\nThe conversation_search tool effectively located LoRA training context using the query \"LoRA training service fine-tuning\" with max_results set to 10. The Desktop Commander read_file tool was used to examine the local Jupyter notebook file, though it revealed the notebook was designed for cloud execution rather than containing embedded Colab links. When searching for technical project details, the conversation_search tool successfully retrieved comprehensive training configuration details including specific model names, dataset identifiers, file paths, and hyperparameters from previous conversations.",
